	url = {http://arxiv.org/abs/2010.04632},
	abstract = {Long-lived radioactive nuclides, such as \${\textasciicircum}\{40\}\$K, \${\textasciicircum}\{232\}\$Th, \${\textasciicircum}\{235\}\$U and \${\textasciicircum}\{238\}\$U, contribute to persistent heat production in the mantle of terrestrial-type planets. As refractory elements, the concentrations of Th and U in a terrestrial exoplanet are implicitly reflected in the photospheric abundances in the stellar host. However, a robust determination of these stellar abundances is difficult in practice owing to the general paucity and weakness of the relevant spectral features. We draw attention to the refractory, \$r-\$process element europium, which may be used as a convenient and practical proxy for the population analysis of radiogenic heating in exoplanetary systems. As a case study, we present a determination of Eu abundances in the photospheres of \${\textbackslash}alpha\$ Cen A and B. We find that europium is depleted with respect to iron by \${\textbackslash}sim\$ 0.1 dex and to silicon by \${\textbackslash}sim\$ 0.15 dex compared to solar in both binary components. To first order, the measured Eu abundances can be converted to the abundances of \${\textasciicircum}\{232\}\$Th, \${\textasciicircum}\{235\}\$U and \${\textasciicircum}\{238\}\$U with observational constraints while the abundance of \${\textasciicircum}\{40\}\$K is approximated independently with a Galactic chemical evolution model. We find that the radiogenic heat budget in an \${\textbackslash}alpha\$-Cen-Earth is \$73.4{\textasciicircum}\{+8.3\}\_\{-6.9\}\$ TW upon its formation and \$8.8{\textasciicircum}\{+1.7\}\_\{-1.3\}\$ TW at the present day, respectively \$23{\textbackslash}pm5\$ \% and \$54{\textbackslash}pm5\$ \% lower than that in the Hadean and modern Earth. As a consequence, mantle convection in an \${\textbackslash}alpha\$-Cen-Earth is expected to be overall weaker than that of the Earth (assuming other conditions are the same) and thus such a planet would be less geologically active, suppressing its long-term potential to recycle its crust and volatiles. With Eu abundances being available for a large sample of Sun-like stars, the proposed approach can extend our ability to make predictions about the nature of other rocky worlds.},
